(16, 'Premises Networks Management', 'Premises Networks Management', '<p style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 1.333em 0px; line-height: 1.333; width: 415px; height: auto; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; \">The corporate finance team within the Manchester office of Baker Tilly has advised on the sale of Cheshire-based Premises Networks to Telent, a UK provider of network and communications services.</p>\n\n<p style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 1.333em 0px; line-height: 1.333; width: 415px; height: auto; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; \">Established in 1996, Premises Networks provides private and public sector organisations with a range of services &ndash; from the supply of single fixed line phones to the design and installation of complex integrated voice and data networks.</p>\n\n<p style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 1.333em 0px; line-height: 1.333; width: 415px; height: auto; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; \">Telent&rsquo;s decision to acquire the business is part of the strategy of its parent, Pension Corporation, to increase market share in the UK. In 2007, the group bought West Midlands-based telecom infrastructure provider, Alan Campbell.</p>\n\n<p style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 1.333em 0px; line-height: 1.333; width: 415px; height: auto; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; \"><strong>Adrian Gare, corporate finance director at Baker Tilly commented:</strong><br />\n<em>&ldquo;This type of acquisition is typical within the IT sector at the moment. Premises Networks is a strong addition to Telent&rsquo;s portfolio of businesses as it has a clear understanding of the telecommunication sector and some very strong partnerships with global vendors such as Aastra and Microsoft. I&rsquo;m confident Telent will be an even stronger force following the deal.&rdquo;</em></p>\n', '<p style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 1.333em 0px; line-height: 1.333; width: 415px; height: auto; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; \">The corporate finance team within the Manchester office of Baker Tilly has advised on the sale of Cheshire-based Premises Networks to Telent, a UK provider of network and communications services.</p>\n\n<p style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 1.333em 0px; line-height: 1.333; width: 415px; height: auto; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; \">Established in 1996, Premises Networks provides private and public sector organisations with a range of services &ndash; from the supply of single fixed line phones to the design and installation of complex integrated voice and data networks.</p>\n\n<p style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 1.333em 0px; line-height: 1.333; width: 415px; height: auto; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; \">Telent&rsquo;s decision to acquire the business is part of the strategy of its parent, Pension Corporation, to increase market share in the UK. In 2007, the group bought West Midlands-based telecom infrastructure provider, Alan Campbell.</p>\n\n<p style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 1.333em 0px; line-height: 1.333; width: 415px; height: auto; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; \"><strong>Adrian Gare, corporate finance director at Baker Tilly commented:</strong><br />\n<em>&ldquo;This type of acquisition is typical within the IT sector at the moment. Premises Networks is a strong addition to Telent&rsquo;s portfolio of businesses as it has a clear understanding of the telecommunication sector and some very strong partnerships with global vendors such as Aastra and Microsoft. I&rsquo;m confident Telent will be an even stronger force following the deal.&rdquo;</em></p>\n', '<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 15px; \">The corporate finance team within the Manchester office of Baker Tilly has advised on the sale of Cheshire-based Premises Networks to Telent, a UK provider of network and communications services.</span></p>\n', '<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 15px; \">The corporate finance team within the Manchester office of Baker Tilly has advised on the sale of Cheshire-based Premises Networks to Telent, a UK provider of network and communications services.</span></p>\n', 18, 0, 1, '2013-03-13 04:24:44', 0, '', 0),
(17, 'OCS London Ltd', 'OCS London Ltd', '<p style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 1.333em 0px; line-height: 1.333; width: 415px; height: auto; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; \">Baker Tilly&rsquo;s M&amp;A and Private Equity team has successfully advised the shareholders on the sale of OCS London Ltd to its management team. The buy-out was supported by Centric Commercial Finance.</p>\n\n<p style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 1.333em 0px; line-height: 1.333; width: 415px; height: auto; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; \">OCS London is a leading courier, mail and media services provider, established in 1958 as the UK independent franchise of OCS Worldwide. With five UK branches and access to a global network spanning more than 200 countries, OCS London provides comprehensive national and international distribution services to a range of clients including The Times, TM Lewin, BMW and The Daily Mail. Having taken ownership of the business, management are keen to drive the business forward, in particular focusing on its successful newspaper subscription service.</p>\n\n<p style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 1.333em 0px; line-height: 1.333; width: 415px; height: auto; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; \">Baker Tilly led the negotiations throughout the process, successfully managing the deal to completion and helping the shareholders realise their investment in full on day one.</p>\n\n<p style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 1.333em 0px; line-height: 1.333; width: 415px; height: auto; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; \"><em>&lsquo;&lsquo;Not only did Baker Tilly secure five offers, they got the deal done despite the uncertainty of the credit crunch! The team kept up the pressure to make sure we completed the deal within a few weeks of agreeing terms. We had no experience of a sale process but Baker Tilly were always on hand to guide us through. Even when things got tough they never lost focus on the end result.&rdquo;</em><br />\n<stron